6.8 7. fill() — Carrying Values Forward or Backward
fill() propagates non-missing values across rows — implementing LOCF and BOCF imputation strategies.

# LOCF: Last Observation Carried Forward for SBP
sbp_locf &lt;- sbp_complete |&gt;
  arrange(USUBJID, VISITNUM) |&gt;
  group_by(USUBJID) |&gt;
  fill(VSSTRESN, .direction = "down") |&gt;   # LOCF
  ungroup() |&gt;
  rename(SBP_locf = VSSTRESN)

# BOCF: Baseline Observation Carried Backward
sbp_bocf &lt;- sbp_complete |&gt;
  arrange(USUBJID, VISITNUM) |&gt;
  group_by(USUBJID) |&gt;
  fill(VSSTRESN, .direction = "up") |&gt;     # BOCF
  ungroup() |&gt;
  rename(SBP_bocf = VSSTRESN)

cat("Remaining missing after LOCF:", sum(is.na(sbp_locf$SBP_locf)), "\n")

#&gt; Remaining missing after LOCF: 0

cat("Remaining missing after BOCF:", sum(is.na(sbp_bocf$SBP_bocf)), "\n")

#&gt; Remaining missing after BOCF: 32








Regulatory caution: LOCF and BOCF are simple imputation approaches that were common in older trials but are no longer considered acceptable as the primary approach for handling missing data in regulatory submissions. Modern guidance (ICH E9 R1) recommends reference-based imputation or mixed models for repeated measures (MMRM). LOCF is useful for sensitivity analyses only.

6.10 9. Full Workflow: SDTM Lab Data → ADaM ADLB-like Structure
Combining all tidyr and dplyr tools into a single ADLB-style preparation:

# Build an ADLB-like dataset for ALT and AST
adlb &lt;- lb |&gt;
  filter(
    LBTESTCD %in% c("ALT", "AST"),
    !is.na(LBSTRESN),
    VISITNUM %in% 1:6
  ) |&gt;
  select(USUBJID, LBTESTCD, VISITNUM, LBSTRESN, LBSTNRHI) |&gt;
  # Add treatment arm from DM
  left_join(
    dm |&gt; select(USUBJID, ARM) |&gt;
      filter(!is.na(ARM), ARM != "Screen Failure"),
    by = "USUBJID"
  ) |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(ARM)) |&gt;
  # Compute ULN ratio
  mutate(
    ULN_ratio  = round(LBSTRESN / LBSTNRHI, 3),
    ULN_flag   = ULN_ratio &gt; 3,   # &gt;3× ULN is a common hepatotoxicity flag
    visit_label = paste0("Visit ", VISITNUM)
  ) |&gt;
  # Pivot: one column per visit for each test
  arrange(USUBJID, LBTESTCD, VISITNUM)

cat("ADLB-like dataset:\n")

#&gt; ADLB-like dataset:

glimpse(adlb)

#&gt; Rows: 1,434
#&gt; Columns: 9
#&gt; $ USUBJID     &lt;chr&gt; "01-701-1015", "01-701-1015", "01-701-1015", "01-701-1015"…
#&gt; $ LBTESTCD    &lt;chr&gt; "ALT", "ALT", "ALT", "AST", "AST", "AST", "ALT", "ALT", "A…
#&gt; $ VISITNUM    &lt;dbl&gt; 1, 4, 5, 1, 4, 5, 1, 4, 5, 1, 4, 5, 1, 4, 5, 1, 4, 5, 1, 4…
#&gt; $ LBSTRESN    &lt;dbl&gt; 27, 41, 18, 40, 33, 21, 23, 30, 38, 21, 25, 30, 26, 30, 29…
#&gt; $ LBSTNRHI    &lt;dbl&gt; 34, 34, 34, 34, 34, 34, 43, 43, 43, 36, 36, 36, 35, 35, 35…
#&gt; $ ARM         &lt;chr&gt; "Placebo", "Placebo", "Placebo", "Placebo", "Placebo", "Pl…
#&gt; $ ULN_ratio   &lt;dbl&gt; 0.794, 1.206, 0.529, 1.176, 0.971, 0.618, 0.535, 0.698, 0.…
#&gt; $ ULN_flag    &lt;lgl&gt; FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FA…
#&gt; $ visit_label &lt;chr&gt; "Visit 1", "Visit 4", "Visit 5", "Visit 1", "Visit 4", "Vi…

cat("\nSubjects with ALT &gt;3× ULN at any visit:\n")

#&gt; 
#&gt; Subjects with ALT &gt;3× ULN at any visit:

adlb |&gt;
  filter(LBTESTCD == "ALT", ULN_flag) |&gt;
